and's Bubble Economy -- tChapter Sixteen. Horizontal and Vertical Inequalities in India -- tChapter Seventeen. Post-Apartheid Changes in South African Inequality -- tConclusion -- tIndex -- tStudies in Social Inequality 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis state-of-the-art volume presents comparative, empirical research on a topic that has long preoccupied scholars, politicians, and everyday citizens: economic inequality. While income and wealth inequality across all populations is the primary focus, the contributions to this book pay special attention to the middle class, a segment often not addressed in inequality literature. Written by leading scholars in the field of economic inequality, all 17 chapters draw on microdata from the databases of LIS, an esteemed cross-national data center based in Luxembourg. Using LIS data to structure a comparative approach, the contributors paint a complex portrait of inequality across affluent countries at the beginning of the 21st century. The volume also trail-blazes new research into inequality in countries newly entering the LIS databases, including Japan, Iceland, India, and South Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aLuxembourg Income Study. 4aLuxembourg Wealth Study. 4across-national affluent countries. 4ahouseholds. 4aincome distribution. 4ainequality. 4amiddle class. 4apublic opinion. 4awealth. 4awomen's work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aGornick, Janet C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJäntti, Markus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804786751zCo-access DOI >